        {
            "id": 1,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "The availability of monoclonal antibodies ( mAbs ) specific for the SARS - coronavirus ( SARS - CoV ) is important for the development of both diagnostic tools and treatment of infection . <S>",
            "relation": "BACKGROUND"
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "parent": 0,
            "text": "A molecular characterization of nine monoclonal antibodies",
            "relation": "ROOT"
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "raised in immune mice ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "parent": 5,
            "text": "using highly purified , inactivated SARS - CoV as the inoculating antigen ,",
            "relation": "MANNER-MEANS"
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "is presented in this report . <S>",
            "relation": "SAME-UNIT"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "These antibodies are specific for numerous viral protein targets ,",
            "relation": "FINDINGS"
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "and six of them are able to effectively neutralize SARS - CoV in vitro ,",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "parent": 7,
            "text": "including one with a neutralizing titre of 0.075 nM. <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "A phylogenetic analysis of the heavy and light chain sequences reveals",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 10,
            "parent": 6,
            "text": "that the mAbs share considerable homology . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "parent": 10,
            "text": "The majority of the heavy chains belong to a single Ig germline V - gene family ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "parent": 11,
            "text": "while considerably more sequence variation is evident in the light chain sequences . <S>",
            "relation": "COMPARISON"
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "parent": 14,
            "text": "These analyses demonstrate",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "parent": 2,
            "text": "that neutralization ability can be correlated with specific murine V H -gene alleles . <S>",
            "relation": "FINDINGS"
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "parent": 14,
            "text": "For instance , one evident trend is high sequence conservation in the V H chains of the neutralizing mAbs , particularly in CDR-1 and CDR-2 . <S>",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "parent": 17,
            "text": "The results suggest",
            "relation": "ATTRIBUTION"
        },
        {
            "id": 17,
            "parent": 14,
            "text": "that optimization of murine mAbs for neutralization of SARS - CoV infection will likely be possible ,",
            "relation": "ELABORATION"
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "parent": 17,
            "text": "and will aid in the development of diagnostic tools and passive treatments for SARS - CoV infection . <S> <P>",
            "relation": "JOINT"
        }
    ]
}